Using the reverse transcription followed by a real-time chain polymerization reaction (rRT-PCR), the test can be performed on respiratory samples obtained using various methods, including the nasopharyngated scull or the expectoration sample.
The results are usually available in a few hours to two days.
The RT-PCR test performed from pharyngated shells is reliable only during the first week of the disease.
The virus may then disappear from the throat while it continues to multiply in the lungs.
